I want to work in social work. I will help children who are abused or neglected. I will also help families who are having problems. My goal is to work in the Division of Family and Children Services.

I have important values for social work. They are service, respect, and being ethical. I also want to help improve relationships between people. I want to improve myself to stay good at my job.

In high school and college, I saw people who did not deal well with problems. They ran away from them or used bad ways to deal with them. This made me think about getting a degree in Psychology. I did not know what I wanted to do after college, so I took a break. One day, I helped a sixteen-year-old boy who was in trouble. I talked to the police and his parents. I saw that I could help children with family problems.

Social justice is also important in social work. People say each person is unique, but they often want to be like others. I am different and do not want to be like everyone else. In high school and college, I stood up for people who were treated unfairly. I wore different clothes, colored my hair, and joined groups that stood for equality. I will continue to fight against unfair treatment.

This paper discusses the Biological and Sociocultural models related to the sleep disorder insomnia. The Biological model focuses on genes and medical aspects. The Sociocultural model looks at social and environmental factors.

This review explains and critiques research about insomnia and these models. It focuses on primary sleep disorders, especially insomnia.

Sleep disorders are problems with sleeping. They can be primary or related to other issues. Primary disorders are problems with falling or staying asleep. Others are related to mental disorders or medical conditions.

The Biological model looks at sleep and wakefulness. Neurons in the brain control sleep. A study with mice found that certain receptors help with sleep. This study shows that sleep problems can be genetic. If these receptors do not work well, sleep can be difficult.

The Sociocultural model looks at social and environmental factors. If sleep problems are genetic, they can be passed down. If receptors do not work well, life can be harder.

This paper explains three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it defines what CAPD is. Next, it tells how to diagnose it. Finally, it gives ways that teachers can help students with CAPD in a classroom.

CAPD is about how the brain uses sound. People with CAPD hear normally, but their brain does not process sound well. It is a problem with the brain, not hearing.

The first mention of CAPD was in the 1950s. It was called “auditory imperception”. Researchers studied children with communication problems. Tests were made in 1961 to understand how the brain uses sound.

CAPD has many signs. People with CAPD may:
- Not hear sounds from different places.
- Have trouble telling sounds apart.
- Not recognize sound patterns.
- Not understand changes in speech.
- Mix up sounds.
- Not understand the order of sounds.

To diagnose CAPD, tests are done. These are done by professionals like audiologists or speech therapists. Many tests use several sounds at once. There is no single test that is always right. There is no known cause for CAPD.

Teachers can help students with CAPD in a classroom. They can use clear speech. They can repeat important information. They can sit close to the student. They can use visual clues. They can make classrooms quiet and calm.

Twelfth Night teaches that while disguise can help with long deception, it is important to stop the deception to keep one's true self. Ending deception can cause problems with friends. Some people will be very angry if they learn they were tricked. The topic of deception in gender role reversal is hard. Why does someone need to be someone else? Viola feels she must be a man to stay safe in a new country. She becomes close to the count, but also has feelings for Orsino. She is happy to finally be herself with Olivia. We are not sure if Olivia loves Cesario or women. Viola's disguise may help Olivia feel what she truly wants.

German colonial rule was known for being very harsh. This is especially true for the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. They were killed in a big way. But the German colonial empire was very different. Each part of it had different rules and ways of doing things. Education was also different in each place. In East Africa, like Tanganyika, many Africans were educated and could read. The Germans did good things there. But in South West Africa, which is now Namibia, education was mostly done by churches. The government did not help much. They helped more with education for white people. This made South West Africa very different from other German colonies. Many people in South West Africa could not read or write. There are many reasons for this. This paper will look into these reasons, especially what settlers and colonial leaders thought about African people.
There are many books about education in the German colonies. Most are in German and were written in the early 1900s. They talked about how education systems worked. Later books in English talked about how education was different in different colonies. Cohen's book compares education in South West Africa and East Africa. He says the big settler population in South West Africa made its education system different. South West Africa had a moderate climate, but much land was very dry. There were more white people there, about 15,000 by 1913, compared to about 5,300 in East Africa.

The music called "Popular Music" has many types. It is hard to list all the types. Most types have many smaller types. The type called "Heavy Metal" has many small types too. It is special because it shows many feelings, but usually dark feelings. It started with people making their own small types. This went on and on to make many types. Now, it is hard to know what Heavy Metal is. It has many ideas from other types of music. Metal music has many words about darkness. The music is loud and strong. People in metal bands play their instruments well. The music has a dark feeling and is like the romantic art of the past. The Beatles song "Helter Skelter" is an example of this dark feeling. The Beatles made this song to be as strong as the Rolling Stones.

Henri Rousseau, a famous Post-Impressionist artist, painted his dreams many years before Surrealists. The Dream, his 1910 painting, shows a woman in a dream. It also shows Rousseau's dream to be accepted by other artists and art lovers. He wanted recognition, acceptance, and praise. He had two choices: follow styles of other artists or be unique. The Dream shows his struggle.

Henri Rousseau was born in Laval, France. He had no formal art training. He worked for France until he was forty. Then he started painting. He lost his first wife and eight children. He painted to feel better. He dreamed of being accepted by the art world.

Rousseau started painting when many other artists were already famous. He wanted to be accepted too. He worked hard but did not get much recognition. He was a folk painter. His dreams were like the average person's.

Matisse and Rousseau were different artists. Matisse wanted to paint in a new way. Rousseau wanted to paint in a simple way to be accepted. They were not the same.

Many great thinkers think ethics and beauty are connected. I believe this is true because John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth is beauty." Most people learn ethics and beauty from school or life. But, we often feel them without being taught. Both ethics and beauty try to explain, not tell us what to do.

Art and morality cannot be fully explained by their qualities. When people talk about art or morality, they often say, "There's just something about it." This "something" is important. It is what makes art and morality powerful. This "something" is like a mystery, like Kant said.

Art and morality affect us deeply, like a dream. They can't be fully explained, but we feel them. Literature, especially, is special. McKean said, "Literature is unique because of its moral quality." Both art and morality have values. This is why they are so important.

Today, Germany is a strong country. It has a unique culture. This culture can be felt from Munich to Kiel. It can also be felt from Cologne on the Rhine River, through the center of Germany, to Dresden on the Elbe River. Germany has come from many different tribes. Germania was the ancestral land of the Germans. The name "Germania" is not certain. Some say it comes from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians. Others say it comes from a word for spear or a word for "shout". The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans. He said they were not mixed with other races. He did not think anyone would leave Rome for Germania. The Germans lived on the borders of the Roman Empire. They traded goods and served in the Roman army.

I looked down, thinking about what I saw. The picture was big and complicated. I was not feeling any emotion. My mind was like a computer, studying but not understanding. Thoughts came and went quickly. I felt like I was just experiencing what I was looking at, not thinking about it.
I had an art book. It taught me how to draw. The book said to look at a picture through a square frame. This makes big pictures easier to see. I tried to do this, but I was amazed by what I saw. I felt like I was looking at art from great artists.
I tried to draw. My hand moved, but not well. The water was smooth. I tried to move the brown thing in the toilet. It did not move. I cleaned it with a mop. It was hard. I wrapped the toilet paper around my hand like a glove. I put my hand in the water. I cleaned the toilet. It was a hard job.

Teenagers are dying in car accidents. Several things cause this problem. The teen brain is not ready for driving. Teens also lack experience. This causes more accidents, vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also have more accidents when they travel with friends.

States try to make teen driving safer by limiting driving hours and passengers. But these rules are not enough. The teen brain is not ready for the risks and responsibilities of driving. A psychologist says even 18 is too young for a full driver's license. Many teens want to take risks for fun. It makes sense to delay driving until this excitement is less.

More teens will start driving in the next few years. This will increase the number of accidents. A simple law could help. Schools could teach driving, but no one under 18 could drive alone. A provisional permit could be issued before a full license. This permit would require some practice driving. A national law would protect teens in all states.

This law is not new.

I looked at many old Edison films in the Library of Congress. There were fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to make illusions. I studied these films to understand their structures. Most trick films from this time are set-bound. They are made in a frontal proscenium. The camera stays in one place. It does not move. They use long and medium shots. Close-ups are not used.

These films often start with actors entering from one side. They move side-to-side. The camera does not follow them. This is like theatre and vaudeville where the audience sees everything at once. The films are short, usually a minute or less. They focus on simple tricks. Some films show the same scene in many ways to make it seem like magic.

For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel, actors move side-to-side. In The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots, a moment shows Mary's "head" appearing, but the film is one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly an agriculturalist but also had a brief political career. These experiences made him known for his strong beliefs in personal freedom and government. His opinions were based on his love for farming. He wanted to keep and grow farming as a good career.

John Taylor believed the United States could create an ideal system because there was no old tradition to hinder it. He believed in natural human rights and that they are all connected. These rights should be beyond the control of the government. In a society, strong people with bad ideas could succeed, but in a civilization, this should not happen.

To create a good society, John Taylor thought a government must understand the good and bad in people. He believed that a good government protects private property and encourages agriculture. He thought a government based on good principles would work fairly, even if led by people with self-interest. Self-interest was good if it created a society based on public good, but bad if it harmed others. A good government was needed to control natural evil, but it must be watched to avoid bad principles.

John Taylor wanted a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted a small federal government with only the powers stated in the Constitution. He knew a big federal government could be expensive and maybe mean. However, he thought a simple interpretation could become corrupt. He also thought the Declaration of Independence was more important than the Constitution because it described the United States as a group of independent states.

Looking at Figure 17, there was a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. This was not good. We are not sure why this happened. It might be because of winter in New England. Fewer people commute by bicycle or on foot. It is also December, when people are busy finishing schoolwork. Many may not think about filling out the commuter log. December also marks the start of the holiday season, when people do not need to come to campus. Classes start late in January. These reasons may explain the low number of logs in February. Some people may also get tired of the project quickly. To fix this, we made a special campaign in March called the Carpool Challenge Week. This campaign helped increase log submissions. But it was hard to keep people interested in the project. This is a common problem in higher education. People like driving their cars. So, we gave out prizes to encourage alternative commuting. We gave gift certificates to local stores. But we could have used bigger prizes, like bicycles or electric cars. If we gave out these prizes later in the project, more people might have participated. The prizes did not change during the project. If we had announced bigger prizes early, more people might have joined.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a type of security. It tracks an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets, like an index fund. But, it trades like a stock. ETFs give you the benefits of diversification and single stock ownership. You can sell short, buy on margin, and buy as few as one share. The costs are low, but you pay a commission for trades. Many ETFs are available.

It's good to check if benefits, like diversification, really exist. We'll examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings. We'll see if owning the ETF is better than buying the top 10 stocks.

We'll only include the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. The chart below shows these holdings and their percentages.

To see if the top 10 holdings represent the ETF well, we'll calculate the Beta and return of a portfolio made up of these stocks. The results show the portfolio made of top 10 holdings has a return 6.11% higher than the ETF. Its Beta is also 0.12 lower. This suggests the top 10 holdings could give a better return and lower risk. But, we need to check if this difference is real.

To check, we'll look at the standard deviation of each top 10 stock and the ETF IHF.

Poe's poem "Dream-Land" is one of his best works. In this poem, he uses the word "Thulé." This word comes from Virgil, who used it to describe an island north of Britain. Poe also knew the works of a German writer named Goethe.
Goethe wrote a poem called "The King of Thule." In this poem, a king loses his wife and cannot stop drinking. He dies after throwing a goblet into the sea. Poe's use of "Thulé" in "Dream-Land" seems to show that he knew this poem by Goethe.
Poe's poem "Dream-Land" can be compared to "The King of Thule." In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a dark, lonely land. This is similar to the feelings of the king in "The King of Thule." Poe may have written "Dream-Land" to show his feelings about his own losses.
Poe's interest in Goethe's work was also influenced by his admiration for the poet Tennyson. Poe probably read "The King of Thule" because of his interest in German literature.

In California, a customer may get punitive damages if they slip and fall in a store. They must prove the store manager acted with malice. The store manager was told twice about the spill. He did not clean it for half an hour because he was eating dinner. The judge will probably not dismiss the case. The customer can argue that the store manager should have known about the danger. He did not take action even after other people were hurt. This is not good conduct. The store manager can be considered to have acted with malicious intent. This is because he was aware of the risk and did not act to avoid it. The customer can sue for damages. The store manager knew about five other slip-and-fall incidents before the customer's accident.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. In class, we talked about whether Islam is a hostile religion. This question is still important today. Since 9/11, media views of Islam have changed. Today, it is hard to imagine a presidential candidate like Barack Obama.

The Prophet Muhammad's story is interesting. I thought he forced people to become Muslims. But his biography says he was humble and kind. People came to him to learn his teachings.

There are similar stories about Muhammad and Jesus. Once, Muhammad multiplied food to feed many people. This makes Muhammad seem like a humble prophet. However, I think this makes Jesus' miracles seem less important.

Many stories in the biography have a third-party perspective. They make the stories seem less true. I do not like this because it makes the stories seem less real.

What bothers me most is that the biography makes Muhammad seem like a good man. But history shows he was not always gentle. I think this is important for Muslims to know.

After Jesus lived, people made new beliefs. These beliefs changed Christian thinking. Today, many people want to understand Jesus' true teachings. They want to know what he said before others added ideas. Many people will follow his ideas. This is happening everywhere. It will happen in the United States and Europe. Christian beliefs and practices will become more like each other. This is like turning back time. It is like what happened when Rome became Christian. It is like how our country changed from slavery to leadership. This change will make people read Jesus' words in a new way. Before Jesus lived, only Judaism existed. People had different beliefs. They were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and normal people.

I think The Jungle shows what humans are like inside. They are usually selfish and only think about their own good. They do not care about others. The book shows this in many ways. The most clear way is with the factory owners and managers. They only want their companies and factories to be big. They do not care about people or animals that get hurt. Sinclair's work says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This shows the big damage the factories do. The owners do not care about the smoke or the animal waste. They also do not care about their workers. They want money more than anything. They force workers to work many hours and can fire them anytime without any warning or help. There were no laws or rules to protect workers. Because of this, the managers could do whatever they wanted. They made workers work in bad conditions. The book does not say this directly, but workers were expected to live and work in those bad conditions. There were no groups to help workers. Unions were formed, but they often did more harm than good. Workers were treated very badly and could not leave. They were like slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors make their readers feel a certain way about important subjects. Some ways are better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these ways in his novel The Great Gatsby. He pairs words that usually do not fit together to make a feeling. He also gives meaning to symbols.

Fitzgerald does this with colors, like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, he makes people think about colors, white/gray and red/pink. He makes these colors mean certain things.

White/gray means the same thing. White is nice and high class. Gray is old and faded. Fitzgerald uses these colors a lot in the beginning of the book. Daisy and Jordan always wear white. Everyone wears white to Gatsby's party, except when Nick is thinking about Gatsby's party. It is gaudy with primary colors.

Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show unimportance. He does this with Daisy. After a long time without using white/gray, he describes Daisy as dressed in white in a white roadster. Readers start to think Daisy is not important, just something Gatsby wants.

Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show Daisy is the same as other people. He says Daisy is in a white dress and has a gray haze on her fur collar. He does this to make Daisy seem like a uniform addition.

San Diego County is good for farming because it has a mild, sunny climate. Many vegetables and fruits grow here. People want organic food. Many farms give tours and let people hike and watch birds.

Organic farming has many good things, like more plants and animals. But it is more work and can cost more money. It needs more labor and management. It also has less efficiency than big farms.

The land chosen is 160 acres near the town of Potrero. It has chaparral, grassland, and oak trees. It is next to Cleveland National Forest. Many rare plants and animals live here, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog.

This land was used by Native Americans for a long time and then by cattle ranchers. I looked at government programs to help a farmer here.

I found an organic farm in the same area. This can be a good example of how to farm this land.

Culture is very important in any negotiation. It can be defined by what it is and what it is not. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not one thing or uniform. Saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are friendly" is not true. Understanding a culture's general ideas is good. But for a negotiator, it is better to know how the culture affects the talks. When you meet a culture different from yours, you compare it to your own. To understand a foreign culture, you can study its history and see its prejudices. Do not judge or change the culture. Accept it and work within its rules, especially in negotiations. If you are in a foreign country, respect its traditions and beliefs. This can help you overcome cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

Culture is not just about national or international differences. Companies within a country also have their own cultures. For example, some companies expect employees to work long hours. Some have relaxed schedules. You can see a company's culture in how employees dress, how they talk, and how they hire people. Some companies allow employees to help charities. Others only allow company-approved charities. The differences in American company cultures show that there is a lot of thought within a culture. Some cultures do not have many differences and may seem uniform, but you should look deeper.

Understanding a culture's values is also important. If a culture values saving face or harmony, a negotiator will not publicly shame his company. If a culture values a hard bargain, a negotiator will not settle early. But before negotiation, learn about your opponent's personal history and beliefs to make the negotiation better.

"The fool says, 'No God.' This is in Psalm 14. St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas both talk about this. They both think God exists. We will compare their ideas. We will start with St. Anselm's idea. He says we can find God in our minds. He thinks we can know God without evidence. He calls this 'faith.' This is different from Thomas Aquinas. He says God can be proven with reason and evidence. He has five arguments. He thinks people can be converted without faith. We will look at their ideas.

In many countries, a prince was born around two hundred and fifty years ago. This prince became a teacher and his teachings became Buddhism. Today, there are many changes in Buddhism. In Sri Lanka, there is a water-cutting ceremony. Monks and people attend this event. Buddha did not teach about this ceremony. Over time, Buddhism has changed. There are many reasons for this change. Some reasons are from people inside Buddhism and others are from people outside Buddhism. Some changes are good and some are bad.

Buddhism has important teachings. These teachings are the triple gem: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is the Buddhist books. These books teach about life, suffering, and how to end the cycle of life and death. Buddhists follow rules for living. Laymen have five rules. Monks have more rules. The main idea of Buddhism is the four noble truths. Life is suffering. Attachment causes suffering. Suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry. This rivalry lasted from 1836 to 1893. The most serious part of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War. This war happened from 1846 to 1848. The United States won this war. It got Texas and the American Southwest as new territory. There were many other conflicts between the two countries. These conflicts ended just before World War I.
The rivalry started because of differences in religion, culture, and tradition. There were also big conflicts over land and resources. Many other countries have rivalries with their neighbors. This is often because they share a border.
The United States and Mexico are not alone in having such rivalries. Many other countries have long-standing rivalries with their neighbors. David M. Pletcher says that only Mexico and Cuba have such long-standing problems with the United States. These countries are geographically close to the United States. They have had rivalries with the United States, while other Latin American countries have had good relations.
Religious issues caused problems between the United States and Mexico. In the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans opposed Catholicism and monarchy. This was similar to the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. However, the ideological struggle between the United States and Mexico was about religion, not politics.
The feelings of distrust between the United States and Mexico came from their former colonial rulers. These feelings made it hard to have good foreign relations.
Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes were about territory and border raids. Schmitt says the rivalry ended as Mexico became more dependent on the United States. It also ended as American ambitions changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by illness. I was a nurse. I chose nursing because it gave me safety and security. I heard, "You will always find work; people will always be sick." So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing.

I was 46 years old and single. I had no money and could not work. I am still disabled. I live on Social Security Disability. I have nothing left that is mine. Every day is a struggle. There is only one thing I know for sure. I could not have survived without my family and friends.

There are always emergencies. Some are too big to overcome alone. We should trust each other and ask for help, not rely on big government. Our forefathers survived with compassion and sharing resources.

I am prepared. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have land and resources to farm, do it. Know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there things that limit how they change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that even today, scientists are not yet able to describe organic forms in mathematical terms. However, now math modeling is used to study some aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis. Our study looks at how math modeling with Prunum, along with experiments, can explain how organisms change. We used X-ray images to measure shell features like whorls, sutures, and the columella. We used these measurements in the CerioShell program. We modeled possible shell shapes to understand how shells change. These results are combined with experiments and descriptions to study long-term changes in Prunum. A shell is like a tube that moves 360 degrees. Each turn is a whorl. Whorls are parts of the shell that spiral around a central line called the columella. The largest whorl is the body whorl. The spire is the part of the shell without the body whorl. A shell has an aperture where the animal comes out. Shells can be seen from different angles: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. To count whorls, start from the first suture and count each turn. A shell can be seen as a path of apertures. This path can be shown mathematically and changed by varying parameters.

Indonesia has not improved neonatal and infant death rates for ten years. The country has met some Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation. But, child and maternal health needs more improvement. The reasons for this problem are discussed below. Health system needs strengthening, not just programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers. But, traditional workers like midwives cannot help in complicated pregnancies. This means many maternal deaths happen from bleeding. Also, less diarrhea cases in children under five are treated by a health professional. Postnatal care rates are low.

Cesarean-section rates are low at 4%. In cities, it's 7%, but in rural areas, it's 2%. This shows healthcare service access is better in cities. There is a 27% difference in service use between the poorest and richest people. This shows the poor have more trouble accessing healthcare.

To improve healthcare, should Indonesia focus on one area or strengthen the whole system? Program-specific approaches are attractive. They have clear goals and fast results. But, they can cause problems. Funding for other areas might suffer. Programs can also waste resources. Multiple programs can cause duplication and uncoordinated services.

Victorian novels focus on details and the rich. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They use mystery and the strange to make characters stronger. They show the characters' feelings and thoughts better.

Oliver Twist has dreams and dream-like states. These show Oliver's pain and fears. The shooting scene makes him very upset. He can't control the event. This shows that Oliver has no power. He is sad because of Fagin. He might be losing his ability to fight back.

Wuthering Heights has a similar dream scene. It shows the main character's pain and anger.

Two years ago, I helped young students in an after-school program. I was good at English and reading. I helped a boy named Adrian, who was in third or fourth grade. He had trouble reading. I thought something was wrong because he knew some letters but not others. He spoke English well, but his mother didn't. I learned that Adrian couldn't read because he didn't know the alphabet. That was hard to believe. I hope Adrian is doing better now.
I tell this story about the language barrier in schools. Especially in California. It's not always easy to see. Even if a child speaks English well, they might have trouble reading. What should we do? In Adrian's case, we needed tutoring in English. But for children who speak little English, it's harder. We need many solutions. We can't just use one thing.
First, the dual language system is a good idea. It helps all children, not just those who speak Spanish. Children in these programs do better in school. Some people think it's a waste of resources. But that's not true. We should have these programs more often. How can we do this? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have bilingual helpers.

Since we are small, we believe in something larger than ourselves. Some learn about it in church or temple. Others search inside. Some believe what their parents teach. But some disagree. They think there is no more than what we know. Every person chooses their own way to understand spirituality. We look for light in darkness.

My father liked birds. His favorite was a cardinal. We sat on our porch, listening to rain. He looked tired. I hugged him, sat close. He stared into rain, looking far away.

My father died in December. He suffered. I did not watch. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not how he died. I stayed in bed for three days. No one called.

The Traditional "Gothic Novel" was called "Old-New" for a reason, as Ian Watt said. The Gothic mode was both liked and disliked. Some people thought it had no real depth. Others liked it for its "terrible sublime" feeling, as Edmund Burke said. The first Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, mixed old and new ideas. It used old theater elements and new novel styles. This made the Gothic genre last for a long time. It became both old and new to people far from the original time. One big Gothic idea is chivalry. Walpole's novel showed this idea. Chivalry is the training of good knights. Gothic writers liked it because it showed good, brave knights. Walpole wrote his novel during a difficult political time. He may have thought good qualities were lost in society. He showed this in his character Frederic. Frederic was described as a brave, courteous knight. This showed chivalry's influence. The Gothic genre became romantic and idealized the past to improve the present.

Supply chain management is a process. It moves goods from customer order to finished product. The term was made in 1982 by Keith Oliver. He said it is about planning, doing, and controlling the process to meet customer needs quickly.

There are six parts of supply chain management: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Production is the first step. Managers need to know what customers want. They look at the market to find out. Then, they decide what to produce and how many. They also choose where to produce and which plant is best. After that, they plan workloads and equipment maintenance.

Supply is the next step. It is about making important decisions. A company may have many divisions. A manager needs to choose which division is best for different parts of the product. The manager may also decide to work with other companies. This is called outsourcing. It helps to be quick and save money.

Ellen Page holds a sign that says, "Hitler is alive in Burma." Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. A military group controls the government. In 2007, people protested the government. Many monks joined the protests. The government stopped the protests with force. A journalist was killed. The government said few people died, but a soldier said more died. This is not new. Many governments try to control people. In China, people protested in 1989. In Rwanda, people were killed in 1990s. Hitler killed many people in the past. Ellen Page's sign is about Burma.

Duke Ellington's music is special. He stayed famous and good for a long time. He was good at making music with his band. His piano playing was not always big, but his songs were good. He wrote songs that showed each player's skills. He made it easy for players to play their own parts. He also wrote songs that made the band sound good together. He did this by using the sound of each player and how they fit with others.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's sound and how he was very good at it. One example is Creole Love Call. In this song, Ellington used voice like a musical instrument. This was before he used lyrics. It shows how he made each soloist sound good. This song has six parts. In each part, different players play different instruments. The way they play shows how Ellington used each player's sound.

In another song, Hot and Bothered, Ellington used his skills again. He used "Bubber" Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing to make a good sound together. In It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington used Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to play a big part on muted trombone.

Ellington made many songs like this. He used each player's sound to make the band sound good together. He added new sounds and made his music very special.

She always felt she needed something. This feeling was strong, and she could not forget it. It began when she was 14. It was still there at 17. She wanted someone, not a thing. But no boy captured her interest. She was confused.

Her family was peaceful. Her parents argued rarely. They argued about her independence. She was strong and fun. She was liked.

Today was different. She heard a scream. She ran to the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground, in pain. She helped her mother. Her mother asked to go to the hospital. She carried her mother to the car and drove.

At the hospital, she called for help. Doctors took her mother. Her mother had fallen from a stool while reaching for a vase.

This study wanted to show that following a "Mediterranean diet" (Med diet) is good for heart health. The aMed diet is a simple version of the Med diet. It has more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, and grains, and less animal products. It also has more good fats (monounsaturated) and less bad fats (saturated).

Before this study, other studies showed that the Med diet helps stop heart disease and death. But they did not look at strokes or stroke deaths.

This study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, for 20 years. They answered food questions six times. More than 95% of the women stayed in the study. The answers were checked with hospital records.

The study showed that women who followed the diet well had less risk of heart disease and stroke. Those in the top group had 30% less risk than those in the bottom group.

In 2007, the United States had a big problem with money. Many people lost their jobs. Many banks and big companies lost money. This was called a recession. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it. The problem started with banks and companies giving special loans to people who could not pay back. This made the economy very weak. The loans were made into hard-to-understand packages and sold to others. When people did not pay back, the banks lost money. This affected the whole economy.

The problem started under the Clinton President in 1999. He wanted to stay in power. He made it easier for people to get loans. This made things worse in the future. A man named Steven Holmes said this could happen. He was right. He said it would be like what happened with banks in the 1980s.

Many things happened that made the economy bad. Loans became very complicated. People and banks gave too much money to the housing market. When the housing bubble burst, many banks lost money. The top five banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts. This was one-third of the USA's money. Banks like Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch did not do well. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion in mortgage debts and were taken over by the government.

Exposition is a part of your story where you introduce important information. It can be helpful or not. It is like the devil on your shoulder telling you to get the past out of the way to get to the good parts.

"Show, don't tell" is a common writing tip. It means to show action and feelings, not just tell the reader what happened. But Dr. Merlin still has problems with exposition. She writes too much and the reader gets bored.

Exposition is when one character tells another a lot of information. In a story, the author does the telling. For example, you read a story and find out the heroine met her husband, they married, and he died. The author should show their love story, not just tell it. We should see the husband's character through his words and actions. We should feel the heroine's love for him.

As a writer, you need to give the reader this information. It is like a bone with some meat on it. You should not rush past this. For example, you introduce a new character. He was in the Air Force, now works at a gas station, married twice, no kids, likes fishing, dreams of owning the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast. Show these details in the story.

I watched two news stories from Columbus, Ohio. The first was about a man in Ashley, Ohio. He stabbed his wife. The news did not say her name, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture and he looked very bad. They talked about this story for two minutes. He was arrested.
The second story was about a shooting. A man named Travis Buyers was injured badly. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area. No one was arrested. The SWAT team was investigating. This story was short. I think it was because he was a black man.
The next story was about a hole in a helicopter. It was hit by a bullet. It was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a five-thousand-dollar reward for information. They also talked about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday. They said the weekend would be warm. They also talked about a robbery at a store near Clime Road. A dark-skinned man robbed the store. He was about six feet tall and weighed 150 pounds. He was wearing a hoodie. They talked about this story for a long time. They mentioned he was black many times. The next story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin. He was sentenced to 300 months for selling drugs. They also said he was Hispanic.

There is a special bond between brothers. This bond is strong and cannot be broken. It makes brothers understand each other. They can see themselves in the other person. Sometimes, this bond can show good or bad feelings. These feelings can cause problems. The story "The Scarlet Ibis" shows this bond. Two brothers go on a journey together. They feel proud and disappointed. One brother dies. The story shows how strong the bond between brothers can be.
The main brother feels pride. He wants his brother to learn many things. But his brother is very sick. The main brother feels angry. He even thinks about killing his brother. But when his brother smiles, he feels love. The main brother loves his brother. This shows that his heart is good.

The brain is a complex information system. People used different metaphors to describe it as technology changed. The brain was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and now to a computer. Remember that these metaphors can be wrong.

Information starts with signals from the senses. These signals are changed by the brain's algorithms in two ways: top-down and bottom-up. For example, when looking at a black box on white, bottom-up processing makes simple things like color and shape into the box. Top-down processing helps you see it as a black box.

After processing, an attention filter decides if information is important. For example, you might hear your name in a loud room. But when looking down, you do not notice blades of grass.

The brain needs to store information. There are short-term, working, and long-term memory. Information is stored in different ways. For example, words can be stored by what they look like, sound like, or mean.

Information in working memory is kept by electrical signals. Information in long-term memory is kept in proteins.

There are many ways to organize knowledge in the brain, like how people remember things, how computers work, and how the brain's cells work. The semantic network model says there are nodes for concepts and links between related nodes.

Aldous Huxley in his novel Brave New World warns about the future threat of technology and capitalism. People in this world value their community over themselves and want immediate happiness. They are controlled from birth by the World Controller. This is like a commentary on modern society, using Marxist ideas.

Capitalism is shown as bad. People do not know about other classes. They only care about their own gains. This is called false consciousness. People in Brave New World are not aware of this. They are happy to consume and spend. This is controlled by the World Controller. The lower classes, like Delta and Gamma, do not know they are controlled. The upper classes know but do not do anything. Relationships between people are not real. People do not feel or love. They only talk about physical appearance. This shows the effect of capitalism. People follow their class.

I live and study at University Park. I have been here two and a half years. It is hard to get around on campus. In my freshman year, I lived in East Halls. It is far from the center. Walking to Willard building could take 25 minutes. Before, there was empty land between East Halls and the school. Now, there are sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As the campus grows, getting around is harder. The best solution is to ride a bike. But, the campus must be built for bikers.

My friend started biking again. He said it is the only way to get around. Biking is good for your body and saves time. I live off campus, far from the center. I bought a bike. Before, it took 25 minutes to walk to Thomas building. Now, it takes 5 minutes on a bike. Pollock Road is the best route. But, it is not always easy. On my bike, I save 30-40 minutes every day. Without a bike, I would need to walk. That would take 2.5 hours every week.
